## Task 1: Create ADR

  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-qwen3-max/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md', content="# ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow\n\n## Status\nAccepted\n\n## Context\nTest-Driven Development (TDD) is a proven methodology for building reliable software, following the red-green-refactor cycle. However, implementing TDD with AI agents presents unique challenges:\n\n1. **Test quality**: AI-generated tests may be too loose (passing without proper validation) or too tight (failing for wrong reasons)\n2. **Refactoring safety**: AI refactoring without proper validation can break functionality\n3. **Pair programming benefits**: Human pair programming uses driver/navigator roles for quality control - this pattern can be adapted for AI agents\n\n## Decision\nImplement a double-agent TDD flow using a driver/navigator pair-programming model with six strict phases:\n\n### Phase 1: Navigator drafts test spec\nThe Navigator (reviewer agent) drafts a test specification describing the expected behavior, edge cases, and validation criteria.\n\n### Phase 2: Driver writes failing test (RED)\nThe Driver (coder agent) writes a test based on the spec. The test **must fail** when executed. If it passes, the spec was insufficient and Navigator revises.\n\n### Phase 3: Driver implements minimum code (GREEN)\nThe Driver writes the minimum code necessary to make the failing test pass.\n\n### Phase 4: Navigator proposes refactor\nThe Navigator reviews the implementation and suggests improvements for code quality, performance, or maintainability.\n\n### Phase 5: Driver applies refactor\nThe Driver implements the suggested refactor.\n\n### Phase 6: Navigator validates\nThe Navigator validates that:\n- All tests still pass\n- The refactor was correctly applied\n- No functionality was broken\n\n## Contract Between Driver and Navigator\n\n### Driver Responsibilities\n- Write tests that fail for the right reasons (RED phase)\n- Implement only the minimum code needed to pass tests (GREEN phase)\n- Faithfully apply refactor suggestions (Refactor phase)\n- Use existing D.U.H. tools (Read, Write, Edit, Bash, etc.)\n\n### Navigator Responsibilities  \n- Provide clear, testable specifications\n- Verify test failures are meaningful (not false positives)\n- Suggest specific, actionable refactor improvements\n- Validate final implementation meets original spec\n\n### Communication Protocol\n- Phase transitions are sequential and mandatory\n- Each phase produces verifiable artifacts:\n  - Phase 1: Test spec document\n  - Phase 2: Failing test file + test execution output\n  - Phase 3: Implementation code + passing test output  \n  - Phase 4: Refactor proposal document\n  - Phase 5: Refactored code\n  - Phase 6: Validation report\n\n## Implementation Approach\n- **Command**: Add `duh tdd` subcommand to CLI\n- **Agents**: Use existing Agent/Reviewer types from `duh/agents.py`\n- **Orchestration**: Implement as a new tool that coordinates the six-phase flow\n- **Testing**: Use stub provider for deterministic end-to-end tests\n- **Integration**: Leverage existing SwarmTool infrastructure for agent coordination\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Single Agent with Self-Review\nA single agent could attempt all phases, but lacks the independent validation that makes pair programming effective. Risk of self-deception in test quality.\n\n### External Test Framework Integration  \nIntegrate directly with pytest/unittest frameworks. This would be more complex and less flexible across different testing frameworks and languages.\n\n### Human-in-the-Loop for Each Phase\nRequire human approval at each phase. This defeats the purpose of automation and would be too slow for practical use.\n\n## Consequences\n**Positive:**\n- Higher quality test suites with proper failure modes\n- Better code quality through enforced refactoring\n- Educational value in demonstrating proper TDD methodology\n- Leverages existing D.U.H. agent infrastructure\n\n**Negative:**\n- Increased token usage due to dual-agent coordination\n- More complex flow requiring careful phase management\n- Potential for phase loops if tests don't fail properly\n\n## References\n- ADR-012: Multi-agent support\n- ADR-063: Coordinator mode and swarm tooling\n- ADR-048: Todo and AskUser tools for user interaction")
